const title = "EKS vs GKE vs AKS cost: a practical comparison checklist";
const description =
  "Compare managed Kubernetes costs across EKS, GKE, and AKS by modeling the same line items: nodes, control plane, load balancers, storage, observability, and egress.";
const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Which is cheaper: EKS, GKE, or AKS?",
    a: "There is no universal winner. Total cost depends on node pricing, control plane fees, traffic patterns (load balancers and egress), observability, and your discount/commitment model. Compare with a consistent set of line items.",
  },
  {
    q: "What data do I need to compare fairly?",
    a: "At minimum: expected pod requests (to estimate node count), target instance types or $/hour, average vs peak utilization, and expected egress/logging volume. If you have regional traffic mix, include it.",
  },
  {
    q: "What's the biggest mistake in managed Kubernetes comparisons?",
    a: "Comparing only node price. In real bills, load balancers, observability, storage, and egress can shift the winner depending on workload.",
  },
];
---
<GuideLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/guides/eks-vs-gke-vs-aks-cost"
  lastUpdated="2026-01-21"
  faqs={faqs}
>
  <p>
    If you're deciding between managed Kubernetes platforms, the best way to compare cost is to model the same set of
    line items for each provider. This avoids "apples vs oranges" (for example, comparing only node prices).
  </p>

  <h2>Start with the same line items</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Worker nodes</strong>: node count x $/hour x billable hours.</li>
    <li><strong>Control plane</strong>: fixed hourly fees (where applicable) and multi-cluster strategy.</li>
    <li><strong>Load balancers / ingress</strong>: hourly + data processing charges depending on product.</li>
    <li><strong>Storage</strong>: persistent volumes, snapshots, object storage, and growth over time.</li>
    <li><strong>Observability</strong>: logs ingestion/retention, metrics series, tracing.</li>
    <li><strong>Egress</strong>: internet egress, NAT, and cross-zone/region transfer.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 1: Normalize capacity (node count)</h2>
  <p>
    Start from workload requests and a realistic allocatable headroom. Use{" "}
    <a href="/calculators/kubernetes-requests-limits-calculator/">Kubernetes Requests &amp; Limits Calculator</a> to get
    a baseline node estimate.
  </p>
  <p class="muted">
    Tip: compare multiple scenarios (average vs peak) instead of using peak 24/7.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 2: Normalize node pricing</h2>
  <p>
    Use an effective blended $/hour that matches your plan (on-demand, commitments, spot mix). Then price the node count
    using <a href="/calculators/kubernetes-node-cost-calculator/">Kubernetes Node Cost Calculator</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 3: Add the "around the cluster" costs</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Control plane</strong>: small for large clusters, but it matters for many small clusters (dev/test,
      multi-tenant environments).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Load balancers</strong>: traffic-heavy workloads can pay more here than expected.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Observability</strong>: logs/metrics often scale with traffic and retention, not just pod count.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Egress</strong>: cross-zone/cross-region and NAT egress can dominate for chatty services.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Shortcuts that still work</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Use a single blended rate per node (or per vCPU/GB) for early planning.</li>
    <li>Model "average month" and "peak month" separately, then bracket the cost.</li>
    <li>Keep add-ons as explicit monthly line items until you have real metrics.</li>
  </ul>

